What the variables mean in each dataset:

School data

school_cd = school id school_name = school name district_name = district name county_name = country name region = region of NYS year total_enroll = total enrollment for the school per_free_lunch = percent of students qualifying for free lunch per_reduced_lunch = percent of students qualifying for reduced price lunch per_lep = percent of students with limited english proficiency mean_ela_score = mean reading score for all grades in the school mean_math_score = mean math score for all grades in the school

ACS data

name = county name year = year county_per_poverty median_household_income county_per_bach = percent over 25 with bachelors degree

OK, so I have determined from the unique number analysis above that the large majority of values for the three percent-based columns are between 0 and 1. I also learned that a value is NA if it is coded as “-99”. So, I will do two things. The first thing I will do is convert the “-99” values into NA values (i.e. I won’t delete them just yet; I’ll hang onto them, just in case I need them). Next, I will exclude the rows where there are values greater than 1 or less than 0 for any of the three percent-based columns; it turns out that the values are in decimal form, instead of percent form.

nys_schools_data$total_enroll[nys_schools_data$total_enroll == -99] = NA
nys_schools_data$per_free_lunch[nys_schools_data$per_free_lunch == -99] = NA
nys_schools_data$per_reduced_lunch[nys_schools_data$per_reduced_lunch == -99] = NA
nys_schools_data$per_lep[nys_schools_data$per_lep == -99] = NA
nys_schools_data$mean_ela_score[nys_schools_data$mean_ela_score == -99] = NA
nys_schools_data$mean_math_score[nys_schools_data$mean_math_score == -99] = NA

In some rows of the nys_schools_data_cleaned, the percent free lunch + percent reduced lunch is greater than 1; it’s possible that there are people who qualify for both free and reduced lunch, but I don’t have that information available. To not complicate the analysis that I will do in future tasks, I will only retain entries where the percent free lunch + percent reduced lunch is less than or equal to 1

nys_schools_data_cleaned <- nys_schools_data_cleaned %>%

I am going to create a high,medium,low poverty variable for each county; I will use the poverty definitions from the Pew Research Center, which are as follows: Low (<= 7 percent in poverty), Medium (between 7 and 23 percent in poverty), and High (>= 23 percent in poverty)

nys_acs_data$Poverty_Level = NA

nys_acs_data$Poverty_Level[nys_acs_data$county_per_poverty <= 0.07] = "Low"

nys_acs_data$Poverty_Level[(nys_acs_data$county_per_poverty > 0.07) & 
                            (nys_acs_data$county_per_poverty < 0.23)] = "Medium"

nys_acs_data$Poverty_Level[nys_acs_data$county_per_poverty >= 0.23] = "High"

Let’s find the average poverty rate of each county over time. Then, we’ll find the counties with the highest 5 and lowest 5 average poverty rates.

Average_Poverty_Rates_Of_Counties = nys_acs_data %>%
  
  group_by(county_name) %>%

Average_Poverty_Rates_Of_Counties[order(Average_Poverty_Rates_Of_Counties$Average_Poverty_Rate, decreasing = T),]

The top 5 counties: Bronx, Kings, Montgomery, Chautauqua, Tompkins The bottom 5 counties: Dutchess, Saratoga, Suffolk, Putnam, Nassau

merged_data %>%

            Mean_ELA_Score = mean(mean_ela_score, na.rm = T),

Task 7: Answering a fundamental question!

What can the data tell us about the relationship between poverty and test performance in New York public schools? Has this relationship changed over time? Is this relationship at all moderated by access to free/reduced price lunch?

Run the following linear regression in merged_data and analyze stat sig (if any)

of coefficients:

ela_scaled_score ~ LOW_POVERTY(dummy var) + HIGH_POVERTY(dummy var) + 100*(per_free_lunch + per_reduced_lunch) + YEAR

math_scaled_score ~ LOW_POVERTY(dummy var) + HIGH_POVERTY(dummy var) + 100*(per_free_lunch + per_reduced_lunch) + YEAR

merged_data$Percent_That_Qualify_For_Free_Or_Reduced_Lunch =

Based on the linear regressions above, there may be a relationship between test performance and poverty level. Interestingly, in both the ELA and Math cases, there is some evidence to suggest that being in a high poverty county does not negatively affect the standardized test score. The regressions also provide evidence of a negative relationship between access to free/reduced lunch and standardized test scores, which could be evidence of moral hazard. Both regressions, on a positive note, seem to suggest that scores are increasing over time in both ELA and math.
